# Migrating `BackgroundProcessor` to .NET 8

## Critical Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown by runtime |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it corrupts application state — it can fire *between* any two IL instructions, leaving locks held and objects half-constructed.

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask Stop(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);

        // Signal cancellation (cooperative stop)
        await _cts.CancelAsync(); // .NET 8+: thread-safe, no sync callbacks

        // Wait for graceful exit with a hard deadline
        if (_workerTask != await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(timeout.Value)))
        {
            // Worker didn't stop in time — log warning, but do NOT
            // force-kill. The token is already signaled; the worker
            // will exit at its next cancellation check.
            Log.Warning("Worker did not stop within {Timeout}", timeout);
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Migration Pitfalls

### 1. Blocking calls ignore cancellation
If `GetNextItem()` blocks on a socket/queue with no timeout, cancellation never fires. **Fix:** use async APIs that accept `CancellationToken`:
```csharp
// ❌ Old: blocks forever, can't cancel
var item = queue.Take();

// ✅ New: responds to cancellation
var item = await channel.Reader.ReadAsync(token);
```

### 2. `volatile bool` is a race condition
The original `_running = false` + `Thread.Sleep(2000)` pattern has no guarantee the worker sees the flag before the abort fires. `CancellationToken` is the correct primitive — it's thread-safe and integrates with async waits.

### 3. Don't catch `OperationCanceledException` broadly
```csharp
// ❌ Swallows cancellation from unrelated tokens
catch (OperationCanceledException) { }

// ✅ Only handle YOUR token's cancellation
catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested) { }
```

### 4. `BackgroundService` is often better
If this runs in ASP.NET Core or a Generic Host app, inherit from `BackgroundService` instead of managing the task yourself:
```csharp
public class MyProcessor : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
            await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
        }
    }
}
// Register: services.AddHostedService<MyProcessor>();
```

### 5. If you must keep synchronous code
Use `CancellationToken` polling inside the loop:
```csharp
private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        var item = GetNextItem(token); // must check token internally
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        ProcessItem(item);
    }
}
```

## Summary

| Concern | .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|---|
| Cancellation | `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationToken` |
| Background work | `new Thread()` | `Task.Run` / `BackgroundService` |
| Blocking I/O | Synchronous | `async`/`await` with token |
| Cleanup | `ThreadAbortException` + `ResetAbort` | `OperationCanceledException` + normal flow |
